			<div class="content" id="post-content-4861823">
									

<p>oh hey it's sooner than I expected nice</p>
<div class="collapsible-block">
<div class="collapsible-block-folded"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">[+]&nbsp;Overall</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded" style="display:none">
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded-link"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">[-]&nbsp;Overall</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-content">
<p>This feels like a good start but the ending feels like it lacks closure and I'm not exactly sure <em>why</em>. I think it's because it just introduces more elements (e.g., the father, the gradual dying) without like, wrapping up any part of the story?</p>
<p>The use of redaction here is universally bad. There are 0 redactions in this piece that I would recommend keeping. Some of them (e.g, the hiding of the date in Addendum -D and the ConProcs) actively harm our ability to understand the chronology of this piece, whereas others remove the spatial context or hide actually shocking details that it'd be better to show.</p>
<p>The description also feels very long, and like it has a very series 1 construction: this is like, shown in the extensive detail and the way it leads with the discovery; and it feels like it could really do with being trimmed a lot.</p>
<p>On the flip side, elements of this aren't necessarily made very clear in a weird way: there's not really any explanation of e.g. why it's kept frozen (obviously it's implied to be 'to preserve the body') or what the purpose of Bosco's audio recording sessions is (as in, what he hopes to achieve from them).</p>
<hr />
<blockquote>
<p>I intended to make the skip both unnerving and sympathetic to the reader/listener. How did I do?</p>
</blockquote>
<p>It feels like you didn't quite manage to do either of these; there's like&#8230;little hints at it being both and there's a definite sense of weirdness in the audio recording; but it feels like it could be developed a little further.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>I presented the series of events in relatively vague terms, and in the order of the Foundation learning about them, which is out of chronological order, so that the reader can piece together the story on their own. Am I being too obvious, not obvious enough, or is there another issue in how this is presented?</p>
</blockquote>
<p>I don't think the ordering is bad per se but it feels like the chronology of the events could be better established in the piece (i.e., it's clear that this is written in the order the foundation finds out about things, but it's not clear how long it takes to go from e.g. Addendum A to Addendum B)</p>
<p>I'm going to tie in my early comments about the emotional impact: it feels like the final three addenda convey the information too&#8230;quickly? Like there's not enough time for us to really dwell on what things mean or explore their implications because it's quickly onto the next implication, y'know?</p>
<blockquote>
<p>Is the length okay? (word count is 2496)</p>
</blockquote>
<p>The length is&#8230;weird. I've kinda talked about this a lot already so I'm not gonna add more elaboration here.</p>
</div>
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded-link"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">[-]&nbsp;Overall</a></div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="collapsible-block">
<div class="collapsible-block-folded"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">[+]&nbsp;Line&nbsp;By&nbsp;Line</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded" style="display:none">
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded-link"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">[-]&nbsp;Line&nbsp;By&nbsp;Line</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-content">
<p><em>Gonna note that I can miss stuff; flag things which are right as being wrong and indeed flag things which are deliberately wrong.</em><br />
<em>I'll likely use <span style="text-decoration: line-through;">strikethrough</span> to indicate stuff to remove and <span style="color: green">green text</span> to indicate stuff to add.</em></p>
<blockquote>
<p>is to be contained in a <span style="text-decoration: line-through;">freezer unit</span> cryogenic preservation tank</p>
</blockquote>
<p>strikethrough is a bad call in ConProcs; like, this one example isn't too bad but the large block of text following it that's struck through sucks and you should use e.g. a 'former containment procedures' collapsible say instead.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>approximately 2&#160;m x .7&#160;m x .7&#160;m.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>These are some precise approximations but like&#8230;if the actual size of the tank doesn't matter enough that approximations are fine, then it doesn't matter enough that you can just, not say what it is.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>Footnote 1: Change approved █/█/████</p>
</blockquote>
<p>this is a shit redaction. I would either cut this footnote or unredact the date.</p>
<blockquote>
<p><span style="text-decoration: line-through;">immediately alert Dr. Bosco if any movement is detected.</span></p>
</blockquote>
<p>This should be e.g. a security team or an MTF say; a single point of failure like this is generally a bad idea.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>SCP-XXXX is the frozen corpse of an Inuit woman between age 25 and 35, dressed mostly in furs, initially discovered in Yukon Territory, Canada at coordinates ██████████.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>This sentence should probably be broken up; though equally several details here could be cut (e.g., the redacted co-ordinates, the age, the clothing).</p>
<blockquote>
<p>SCP-XXXX was discovered when villagers in ████ informed the local police about an unidentified animal crawling in the snow in an erratic movement pattern.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>IMO: tell us more about the anomaly before telling us how it was found.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>Footnote 2: Quoted from two separate witnesses</p>
</blockquote>
<p>this isn't a witness quote; it might be witness testimony but it's not directly quoting them.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>The Foundation was able to easily locate and contain SCP-XXXX using basic tracking methods.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>basic tracking methods would help them locate the SCP but not contain it; I would move it's mention around a little so it doesn't imply they did both.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>Amnestics were deemed unnecessary for the villagers and police, who were unable to accurately describe the creature consistently.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>This is a really poor reason to not amnesticise someone.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>SCP-XXXX is bisected in a jagged pattern approximately 6&#160;cm below the naval.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>this feels like the kind of detail you should mention right at the start of describing the SCP</p>
<blockquote>
<p>While thawed, the neurons present throughout SCP-XXXX-2, which will be referred to as SCP-XXXX-3,</p>
</blockquote>
<p>I really don't think the -3 designation is necessary; every time you use it, it feels like you could just as easily say -2 without loss of meaning.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>During locomotion, SCP-XXXX-2 primarily utilizes the legs’ muscle tissue to bend the knees, thighs, and ankles, and drag itself across the ground. To do so, the muscles controlled by SCP-XXXX-3 often bend the legs at unnatural axes and angles, due to the degradation of the bone and ligament tissue. The anterior half of the left foot, at the time of the first observation session, was bent upwards toward the knee, perpendicular to heel, but SCP-XXXX-2 was able to bend the foot back into place, seemingly at will. SCP-XXXX-2 frequently hyperextends the knees at an angle of roughly 60 degrees. Under ordinary circumstances, this would damage the muscles so that they would be unable to move properly, but SCP-XXXX-3 appears to either repair or replace the torn muscles at a rapid pace, so that the knees can quickly bend back to a natural angle.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>This is, by far, too much detail.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>Addendum XXXX-A: Third observation session audio recording</p>
</blockquote>
<p>I would put the transcript inside a block quote; and ideally add e.g. dialogue tags: like, actually format it as an interview using the template in the <a href="/how-to-write-an-scp">How to Write an SCP guide</a>.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>It’s almost like a toddler learning to walk and falling on its behind, which is exactly what happened. Actually, now that I think of it, that might theoretically make sense if it has a toddler’s motor abilities since the fetus was never—</p>
</blockquote>
<p>Something about this feels&#8230;unsatisfyingly expository? iunno, it might just be me; but it feels like we can be left to assume 'oh it's cos it's a baby'</p>
<blockquote>
<p>[A clap is heard]</p>
<p>Ow, stop that! Ow, ow, stop, stop, get off, jeez!</p>
</blockquote>
<p>This feels like it's a little too vague about what happened here?</p>
<blockquote>
<p>Most speculated the sound was made by SCP-XXXX, suggesting it was [REDACTED].</p>
</blockquote>
<p>Not really a fan of this redaction; it feels like anything you say here would be more interesting than not saying anything at all.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>the father refused to provide any assistance</p>
</blockquote>
<p>it's unclear whether this is 'the father of the child' or 'the father of the pregnant woman' at this point; and even the reference to her being a 'stupid whore' feels&#8230;like it doesn't provide clarity</p>
</div>
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded-link"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">[-]&nbsp;Line&nbsp;By&nbsp;Line</a></div>
</div>
</div>

