			<div class="content" id="post-content-4863256">
									

<p>Thanks, this is good advice; I'm already getting ideas of how to change and improve this as I read it. I'd like to ask a couple of questions to help me decide on my how to implement my new ideas, do you think these would work?</p>
<p>-It sounds like I should be focusing less on the open-mystery aspect that lots of SCPs (especially earlier ones) tend to use, and focus more on disclosing a full story with only small amounts of vague subtleties, is that somewhat accurate? Admittedly I am taking inspiration more from Series 1 than the more recent series.</p>
<p>-I'm thinking one of the best ways to clarify the story in the addenda is to turn Addendum 3 into full interviews with the father and the doctor, which will also disclose more origin story material for the skip, and make it more relatable/sympathetic. Does this sound like something that would work? Would the Foundation do something like that, i.e. visit them in person under the guise of a separate government organization, instead of just making a phone call?</p>
<p>-I can definitely shorten the description by at least 20-25%, maybe almost half. I get the impression that I should instead put almost all of my focus into the addenda. I think 3000 words total would be the high end I should go for, but would that seem disproportionate to put so much of the material into these sections? Most SCPs I see tend not to have more than 5 addenda, unless it's intended as a lengthy epic.</p>
<p>-The &quot;closure&quot; I intend to make is that the creature's desire is to achieve closure with the father character by meeting him. This is something that I think the Foundation would never allow even if they understood that's what it wants, which is why I don't end with a solid conclusion, but rather with the indefinite freezing, to imply it never gets what it wants (though I intend to modify the specifics here). Do you disagree, and feel the creature should achieve this?</p>

