																		Re: Draft: Frozen Corpse and Nervous System
															</div>
				<div class="info">
					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/cybersqyd" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(5336470); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=5336470&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610226577" alt="cybersqyd" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=5336470)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/cybersqyd" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(5336470); return false;" >cybersqyd</a></span> <span class="odate time_1609923304 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">06 Jan 2021 08:55</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-4863551">
									

<div class="collapsible-block">
<div class="collapsible-block-folded"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">[+]&nbsp;Open&nbsp;for&nbsp;answers&nbsp;to&nbsp;your&nbsp;questions</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded" style="display:none">
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded-link"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">–&nbsp;hide&nbsp;block</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-content">
<blockquote>
<p>It sounds like I should be focusing less on the open-mystery aspect that lots of SCPs (especially earlier ones) tend to use, and focus more on disclosing a full story with only small amounts of vague subtleties, is that somewhat accurate? Admittedly I am taking inspiration more from Series 1 than the more recent series.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>Open mystery is like&#8230;fine when you have a concept that supports this: like, <a href="/scp-4391">SCP-4391</a> is a relatively recent example of something that's just, openly highly mysterious about what's going on. The problem here is that the mystery of this&#8230;just isn't necessarily very interesting? Which is why a more concrete narrative arc is a good idea (which doesn't mean 'don't be subtle', it just means, 'the subtlety has to actually add something')</p>
<blockquote>
<p>I'm thinking one of the best ways to clarify the story in the addenda is to turn Addendum 3 into full interviews with the father and the doctor, which will also disclose more origin story material for the skip, and make it more relatable/sympathetic. Does this sound like something that would work? Would the Foundation do something like that, i.e. visit them in person under the guise of a separate government organization, instead of just making a phone call?</p>
</blockquote>
<p>My, concern with this is that it feels like it would add a lot of backstory to this without really adding much that's interesting (i.e., that this feels too much like an info dump of material that doesn't necessarily add a tonne).</p>
<blockquote>
<p>I can definitely shorten the description by at least 20-25%, maybe almost half. I get the impression that I should instead put almost all of my focus into the addenda. I think 3000 words total would be the high end I should go for, but would that seem disproportionate to put so much of the material into these sections? Most SCPs I see tend not to have more than 5 addenda, unless it's intended as a lengthy epic.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>I don't think this is a huge concern tbh. Like, use as many addendum and as many words as you need to convey what you need to: the problem with the description is that it provides a lot of detail that covers how it works exactly that like, the first addendum directly shows in a more effective/interesting manner.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>The &quot;closure&quot; I intend to make is that the creature's desire is to achieve closure with the father character by meeting him. This is something that I think the Foundation would never allow even if they understood that's what it wants, which is why I don't end with a solid conclusion, but rather with the indefinite freezing, to imply it never gets what it wants (though I intend to modify the specifics here). Do you disagree, and feel the creature should achieve this?</p>
</blockquote>
<p>See, the indefinite freezing <em>can</em> grant closure, it just doesn't here. For it to work, it has to provoke an emotional reaction in the reader: we have to want the SCP to reach the father because we think e.g. it would achieve something, perhaps a sense of closure for the SCP, perhaps a partial/full reversal of the situation, perhaps allowing the SCP to get revenge say; and then for us to be invested in this happening; so that a final note saying e.g. 'due to budget concerns, further testing has been suspended indefinitely.' lands because we actually care.</p>
<p>In the current version, the indefinite freezing doesn't land because it's effectively the status quo already: it's not a new development.</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>

