			<div class="content" id="post-content-4863389">
									

<div class="collapsible-block">
<div class="collapsible-block-folded"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">+&nbsp;show&nbsp;block</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded" style="display:none">
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded-link"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">–&nbsp;hide&nbsp;block</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-content">
<ul>
<li><strong>Conprocs</strong>: I think you should cut the specific dimensions of the containment unit. Such specific dimensions are always a bad idea… what if it is 6cm smaller than the requirement? Does containment fail then? Instead suggest just saying it is contained in a <em>cryogenic preservation tank</em> and leaving out the dimensions.
<ul>
<li>Moreover, I think you should cut all the bits that are crossed out. I personally think crossing out in a digital document (which this clearly is) makes no sense. This is a living document, so if there was an update, and it is <em>necessary</em> to tell the reader about, break it out into a collapsible. BUT, personally, I would suggest cutting them entirely. As I don’t think you would lose anything.</li>
<li>Finally, I would suggest simplifying the closing sentence. Most of those details can be assumed (locking of doors and only approved personnel should be allowed to observe, etc)</li>
</ul>
</li>
</ul>
<ul>
<li><strong>Redactions</strong>: I think you should get rid of all the redactions here. They serve little purpose, just make up or find real world locations… make up dates. Think about it like this, you are reading a classified document and assumedly from a position of approval, so why would the documents be redacted for the reader? Redactions usually only occur when a classified document is released to the public… that’s not what is happening in 99% of SCPs.</li>
</ul>
<ul>
<li><strong>Description</strong>: You’ve got a lot of bloat here, I would suggest trimming it down to roughly 50-60% of the words you currently have. Consider that anything provided just for context is easily cut… the Description should just be what is necessary for the understanding of the story. For example, most of the second paragraph concerning the discovery seems like information we could assume.
<ul>
<li>Also, you want to start off with the primary description… so anything about the discovery should come later.</li>
<li>I don’t understand why -1 is designated at all, as there seems to be nothing anomalous about the top half of the corpse.</li>
<li>I think there’s way too much information about the lower half’s locomotion.</li>
<li>The second to last paragraph seems like speculation, which doesn’t really belong in a description (as this is “what we know” not what “we are wondering about”) and also don’t think it adds much</li>
<li>Why does -3 match the genetics of -1 but not -2, isn’t -1 and -2 just two halves of the corpse of a woman?</li>
</ul>
</li>
</ul>
<ul>
<li><strong>Addendum-A</strong>: I think you should format the transcript, to show it as a separate document. There are simplistic templates on the Wiki syntax page: <a href="http://scp-wiki.wikidot.com/wiki-syntax#toc5">http://scp-wiki.wikidot.com/wiki-syntax#toc5</a>
<ul>
<li>Why would the doctor let it out into the halls? What research purpose would this serve?</li>
</ul>
</li>
</ul>
<ul>
<li><strong>Addendum-B</strong>: I would suggest cutting this entirely, and adding a tiny bit to the transcrpipt like: “vocalization other than Dr. Bosco can be heard. Dr. Bosco does not respond or acknowledge the vocalization.” This would be much creepier, and would suggest people listen to the recording itself. <em>The reason I am suggesting you cut this addendum is its redundant, and suffers from “telling not showing,” especially when you’ve already done the business with the recording.</em></li>
</ul>
<ul>
<li><strong>Addendum-C</strong>: You don’t really have an ending here, there’s no climax or resolution to the story. A lot of buildup, leading to the revelation that the thing can talk on the audio recording and is searching for its dad… but then you go back and spend three paragraphs trying to figure out who the woman was. Why is it needed to be assumed, is there no fingerprinting, or dental records of this individual? Moreover… I don’t think it’s a satisfying ending to merely try to identify the corpse. We could never know anything about her and it wouldn’t make the article worse…
<ul>
<li>I think you need a stinger of some sort, and some thought needs to be put into how you want this ending to sit with the reader. Is this a haunting piece? Do you want to imply an emotional resolution is possible? As it is, it lands very flat.</li>
</ul>
</li>
</ul>
</div>
</div>
